# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: coconut-shy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:coconut-shy/aunt-sally] It was suggested by James Redding Ware that the term was based on a blackface doll, itself inspired by a low-life character named "Black Sal," which appeared in an 1821 novel entitled *Life in London* by Pierce Egan, a contemporary of Charles Dickens.
[src:coconut-shy/aunt-sally] The game dates back to the 17th century, although the name "Aunt Sally" may have been a later addition.
[src:coconut-shy/aunt-sally] It was traditionally played in central English pubs and fairgrounds.
[src:coconut-shy/aunt-sally] An Aunt Sally was originally the modelled head of an old woman with a clay pipe in her mouth; the object was for players to throw sticks at the head in order to break the pipe.
[src:coconut-shy/aunt-sally] The target has also been a puppet, live person, or a simple ball on a stick.
[src:coconut-shy/aunt-sally] There are also other theories of how the game started.
[src:coconut-shy/aunt-sally] One such theory is that a live cockerel was placed on the stick, and people would throw sticks at it.
[src:coconut-shy/aunt-sally] Whoever killed it won the game and took home the chicken.
[src:coconut-shy/aunt-sally] Another theory is that in Port Meadow in Oxfordshire, at the time of the English Civil War, the Cavaliers (soldiers loyal to King Charles I) were bored and formed a game with sticks and makeshift materials similar to the game as understood today.
[src:coconut-shy/aunt-sally] The game has also been played outside of the UK; picnic attendees were reported to play Aunt Sally in Australia in the 1880s.
[src:coconut-shy/aunt-sally] Today, the game of Aunt Sally is still played as a pub game in Berkshire, Buckinghamshire, Gloucestershire, Oxfordshire, Northamptonshire and Warwickshire.
[src:coconut-shy/aunt-sally] In 2011 the inaugural Aunt Sally Singles World Championship took place at the Charlbury Beer Festival in Charlbury, West Oxfordshire.
[src:coconut-shy/aunt-sally] Among the attendees was Prime Minister David Cameron.
[src:coconut-shy/aunt-sally] The tournament has continued there annually ever since.
[src:coconut-shy/aunt-sally] On 24 August 2019, the first world championship for Aunt Sally pairs was held in the Bull, Launton, Oxfordshire, and was won by the pub team from The Bell, Bicester.
[src:coconut-shy/aunt-sally] Darren Moore and Billy Craig were the winners.
[src:coconut-shy/aunt-sally] Runners-up were Aimee Sheehan and Christopher Hulme.
[src:coconut-shy/aunt-sally] The game bears some resemblance to a coconut shy or skittles but with teams.
[src:coconut-shy/aunt-sally] Each team consists of eight players or five players depending on the local league.
[src:coconut-shy/aunt-sally] The ball is on a short plinth about 4 to 6 inches (100 to 150 mm) high by 3 inches (75 mm) diameter, known as the "dolly", which is placed on a dog-legged metal spike (the swivel) about 30 to 40 inches (750 mm to 1000 mm) high.
[src:coconut-shy/aunt-sally] Players throw sticks or short battens, about 18 by 2 inches (450 x 50 mm) at the dolly, from ten yards away, trying to knock it off without hitting the spike.
[src:coconut-shy/aunt-sally] Successfully hitting the dolly off is known as a "doll"; however, if the spike is hit first, then the score does not count and is called an "iron".
[src:coconut-shy/aunt-sally] A zero score (after 6 sticks are thrown) is known as a "blob" and marked with an X on the scoreboard.
[src:coconut-shy/aunt-sally] If all legs are a blob the person is a "blobber".
[src:coconut-shy/british-folk-sports] This page lists sports and games which have traditionally been played in rural areas.
[src:coconut-shy/british-folk-sports] Some take the form of annual events in a particular location associated with the tradition.
[src:coconut-shy/british-folk-sports] Others have become more widespread, being played in local fairs or festivities in different areas.
[src:coconut-shy/british-folk-sports] Many remain somewhat obscure, and perhaps due to their unusual or quirky nature, have not developed into established sports.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] The common borders the River Cam and houseboats are often moored on the common's bank.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] The boathouses of most of the colleges of Cambridge University are on the opposite bank.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] In 1874, Midsummer Common was scene to the notorious murder of Emma Rolfe.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] Regular major events held on the Common include The May Day Fair, Strawberry Fair and fireworks on Guy Fawkes Night, 5 November, which regularly attract around 25,000 people.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] Other events include fun runs and cycling events where the common is used as a start and finish point.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] A vigil and lantern floating ceremony took place on the common on Hiroshima Memorial Day in 2006.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] Cambridge Midsummer Fair was granted a charter by King John in 1211, and was originally held on or near the feast of St Etheldreda.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] Originally a trade fair, income from the event went to the Barnwell Priory.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] In the sixteenth century the council and Mayor of Cambridge acquired the rights for the midsummer fair, with University Proctors retaining the right to search the fair for beggars, vagabonds and lewd women.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] The latter right in particular was hotly disputed.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] In the 18th century it was named the Pot fair due to the quantity of china traded there, and it was popular among gypsy travellers for trade in horse and cattle.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] In more recent times it has become a pleasure fair with amusements taking the place of trade in goods.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] It is heavily attended and has recently given rise to problems of safety and public order and with litter.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] In March 2006 Geoffrey King, who later became the chairman of the Friends of Midsummer Common, put up £20 to investigate the possibility of introducing a "residents' herd" of cows to the common, at a meeting of the Brunswick and North Kite Residents' Association.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] On 7 April 2007, when there had been no cattle on the common for a number of years, a small number of Red Poll bullocks, owned by a Cambridge resident, were introduced to the common.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] The grazing of cattle on the common is controversial, given the other uses to which the common is put, which may conflict with grazing.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] Midsummer Common is registered under the Commons Registration Act 1965.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] Jesus Green was separated from Midsummer Common in 1890 when Victoria Avenue was built.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] Jesus Green is no longer maintained in a state suitable for grazing.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] In 1930, Jesus College exchanged land between what is now the Cutter Ferry bridge and Elizabeth Way for part of Butt's Green on the Jesus College side of Victoria Avenue.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] Butt's Green is an area which, historically used for archery butts, is now part of Midsummer Common.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] The Butt's Green area is less disturbed by events than the other areas and tends to have a wider diversity of plant life.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] Midsummer Common, along with wide swathes of Cambridge City, has been a designated area under the Anti-social Behaviour Act 2003, s 20(3)-(5).
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] During much of Winter 2006/07 this order only applied in the evenings and apparently applied to the whole common; as of February 2007 a new authorisation which was brought into force on 3 January 2006 and lasting for six months was publicised.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] This only applied to the boundary path, and one corner of the common.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] The area of the common designated under the act does not include the public toilets or the area in which half of the city's redeployable CCTV cameras have been deployed within 100 m of each other.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] This applies to a large area of Cambridge including Mill Road, Parker's Piece, Christ's Pieces, Midsummer Common, Brunswick Gardens and Riverside.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] The notice state that the order has been made with the consent of the City Council.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] Past practice suggests that this would have been given by a "Leader's decision".
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] Council policy states that such decisions must be reported to [party] Group Leaders immediately and to the next available meeting of the Scrutiny Committee – no such decision was brought to the Scrutiny meeting on 10 January 2007.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] Cambridge City Council believe that a Designated Public Places Order cannot be applied to the common, such an order might be a more appropriate manner of dealing with alcohol-related anti-social behaviour on the common.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] The Friends of Midsummer Common was inaugurated in October 2006, initially made up of owners of residential property surrounding the common.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] Its founding chairman was Geoffrey King who resigned from the Brunswick & North Kite Residents Association before setting up the Friends of Midsummer Common.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] Their objectives include: "to work with organisers to ensure that events have minimal impact and cause no nuisance to local residents;".
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] Alistair Wilson, Cambridge City Council's Green Space Manager was reported to have wanted a Friends of Midsummer Common group set up in May 2006.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] Camboaters Community Association is an association of residential boaters on the River Cam.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] The local residents' association Brunswick & North Kite Residents Association, BruNK, (now dormant) also made representations to the city council regarding the common.
[src:coconut-shy/cambridge-midsummer-fair] The Midsummer House restaurant, which currently holds 2 Michelin Stars, and the Fort St George public house are both on the riverside on the common.
[src:coconut-shy/cock-throwing] Cock throwing was a popular pastime with people of all classes, especially with children, and although widespread, was less common than cockfighting.
[src:coconut-shy/cock-throwing] Sir Thomas More referred to his skill in casting a cokstele as a boy.
[src:coconut-shy/cock-throwing] If the bird had its legs broken or was lamed during the event, it was sometimes supported with sticks in order to prolong the game.
[src:coconut-shy/cock-throwing] The cock was also sometimes placed inside an earthenware jar to prevent it from moving.
[src:coconut-shy/cock-throwing] Variations on the theme included goose quailing (or squailing), when a goose was substituted, and cock thrashing or cock whipping, which involved a cock being placed in a pit where the blindfolded participants would attempt to hit it with their sticks.
[src:coconut-shy/cock-throwing] A Sussex variation was similar to bull-baiting with the rooster tied to a 4-or-5-foot-long (1.2 or 1.5 m) cord.
[src:coconut-shy/cock-throwing] In 1660, an official pronouncement by Puritan officials in Bristol to forbid cock throwing (as well as cat and dog tossing) on Shrove Tuesday resulted in a riot by the apprentices.
[src:coconut-shy/cock-throwing] Cock throwing's popularity slowly waned in England, as social values changed and animal welfare became a concern.
[src:coconut-shy/cock-throwing] William Hogarth depicted it as a barbarous activity, the first stage in a "slippery slope", in *The Four Stages of Cruelty* in 1751, and Nathan Drake credited this in part for changes in public attitudes to the sport.
[src:coconut-shy/cock-throwing] From the middle of the 18th century, magistrates began to deal with the problem more harshly, a marker of its loss in popularity among the "respectable" classes, imposing fines for public order offences, and local by-laws banned the practice in many places.
[src:coconut-shy/cock-throwing] By the early 19th century, the tradition was all but forgotten, lingering as isolated incidents into the 1840s.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut-shy] A **coconut shy** (or **coconut shie**) is a traditional British game frequently found as a sidestall at funfairs and fêtes.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut-shy] The game consists of throwing wooden balls at a row of coconuts balanced on posts.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut-shy] Typically a player buys three balls and wins when each coconut is successfully dislodged.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut-shy] In some cases other prizes may be won instead of the coconuts.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut-shy] The word "shy" in this context means to toss or throw.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut-shy] The origins of the game are unclear, but early references to it appear in the late 1800s.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut-shy] It probably derives from the game of Aunt Sally, with coconuts being seen as an exotic prize in the late 19th century and into the 20th century.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut-shy] The National Fairground Archive holds a photograph of a coconut shy dating from 1890.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut-shy] The game is mentioned by Graham Greene in *The Ministry of Fear* in 1943, H.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut-shy] Wells in *The Invisible Man* in 1897, by E.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut-shy] Nesbit in *The Story of the Treasure Seekers* in 1899, and by P.G.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut-shy] Wodehouse in the short story "The Purity of the Turf".
[src:coconut-shy/coconut-shy] The term is first listed in the *Oxford English Dictionary* in 1903.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut-shy] One theory suggests the coconut shy may have originated at the annual Pleasure Fair in Kingston upon Thames in 1867.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut-shy] That event took place on the town's Fairfield, not far from a coconut fibre mill on the Hogsmill river.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut-shy] All descriptions of mats in cocoa nut fibre made to order wholesale".
[src:coconut-shy/coconut-shy] Today the only reminder of Kingston's association with coconuts is a pub in Mill Street, which was the principal route between Fairfield and Middle Mill for several centuries.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut-shy] Called "The Cocoanut", it is not only spelled the old way but is furthermore the only pub in Britain with that name.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut-shy] However, there is a similar game shown in etchings by Thomas Rowlandson.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut-shy] *Sketch on York Race Ground* (1804) shows a carnival game in which sticks are thrown at various shaped objects atop posts; the drawing was etched and printed in 1805 titled *Gaffers at a Country Fair*, and a revised version was printed in 1808 titled *Doncaster Fair the Industrious Yorkshirebites*.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut-shy] An image in the lower left corner of *A Prospect of Greenwich Fair*, from *Manners and Cvstoms of ye Englyshe in 1849*, no 13, Getty Images, shows the same game with taller poles and the coconuts shown atop them.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut-shy] According to a source described as an official from the Showman's Guild, coconut shies began at the Cambridge Midsummer Fair with cockerels as the targets rather than coconuts.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut-shy] In German-speaking countries the game of *Dosenwerfen* (throw cans) is popular for school parties, as well as in professional stalls at fairgrounds.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut-shy] It involves throwing balls at stacks of empty tin cans.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut-shy] In France, a similar game known as *Chamboule-Tout* is frequently found at fun fairs.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut-shy] In the U.S. and Canada, milk cans are commonly used.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The **coconut** (***Cocos nucifera***) is a member of the palm family (Arecaceae) and the only living species of the genus ***Cocos***.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The term "coconut" (or the archaic "**cocoanut**") can denote the whole **coconut palm** tree or the large hard fruit.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Originally native to the Central Indo-Pacific, they are ubiquitous in coastal tropical regions.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The coconut tree provides food, fuel, cosmetics, folk medicine and building materials.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The inner flesh of the mature fruit forms a regular part of the diets of many people in the tropics and subtropics.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coconut endosperm contains a large quantity of a liquid, "coconut water".
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Mature coconuts can be processed for oil and coconut milk from the flesh, charcoal from the hard shell, and coir from the fibrous husk.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Dried coconut flesh is called copra, and the oil and milk derived from it are commonly used in cooking and in soaps and cosmetics.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Sweet coconut sap can be made into drinks or fermented into palm wine or coconut vinegar.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The hard shells, fibrous husks and long pinnate leaves are used to make products for furnishing and decoration.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The coconut has cultural and religious significance for Austronesian peoples, appearing in their mythologies, songs, and oral traditions.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] It has religious significance in South Asian cultures, where it is used in Hindu rituals including weddings and worship.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Trees can grow up to 30 metres (100 feet) tall and can yield up to 75 fruits per year, though fewer than 30 is more typical.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] They are intolerant to cold and prefer copious precipitation and full sunlight.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Many insect pests and diseases affect commercial production.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] In 2024, world production of coconuts was 65.5 million tonnes, with 73% of the total produced by Indonesia, India, and the Philippines.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The coconut is monoecious, meaning that both male and female flowers grow on the same tree, in its case in the same inflorescence.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] It is possible that the species in addition occasionally has bisexual flowers.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The female flower is much larger than the male flower.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Mature trees grow continuously, producing leaves, flowers, and fruit all year round.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] It takes some 14 months for each flower primordium to develop into an inflorescence, botanically a spadix inside a sheathing spathe.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] A healthy tree can produce up to 15 inflorescences per year, staggered so that there is always a mature one with others in different stages of development.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] It takes 11 months from the opening of the female flowers to the time of harvest.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coconut palms are largely cross-pollinated, although most dwarf varieties are self-pollinating.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Botanically, the coconut fruit is a drupe, not a true nut.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Like other fruits, it has three layers: the exocarp, mesocarp, and endocarp.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The exocarp is the glossy outer skin, usually yellow-green to yellow-brown in color.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The mesocarp is composed of a fiber, called coir, which has many traditional and commercial uses.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The exocarp and the mesocarp make up the "husk" of the coconut, while the endocarp makes up the hard coconut "shell".
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The endocarp is around 4 millimetres (1⁄8 inch) thick and has three distinctive germination pores (micropyles) on the distal end.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Two of the pores are plugged (the "eyes"), while one is functional.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The interior of the endocarp is hollow and is lined with a thin brown seed coat, some 0.2 mm (1⁄64 in) thick.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The endocarp is initially filled with a liquid endosperm (the coconut water).
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The liquid contains many free cell nuclei (it is multinucleate) dividing by mitosis, without cell boundaries.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] As development continues, cellular layers of endosperm deposit along the walls of the endocarp up to 11 mm (3⁄8 in) thick, starting at the far end.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] They eventually form the edible solid endosperm ("coconut meat") which hardens over time.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The small cylindrical embryo is embedded in the solid endosperm directly below the functional pore.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] During germination, the embryo pushes out of the functional pore and forms a haustorium inside the central cavity.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] This absorbs the solid endosperm to nourish the seedling.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Wild *niu kafa* coconuts feature an elongated triangular fruit with a thicker husk and a smaller amount of endosperm.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] These make the fruits more buoyant, ideal for ocean dispersal.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Domesticated *niu vai* Pacific coconuts are rounded in shape with a thinner husk, more endosperm, and more coconut water.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] A full-sized fruit weighs about 1.4 kilograms (3 pounds 1 ounce) depending on variety.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The 21st century Bido variety from Indonesia averages 3.158 kilograms (6 pounds 15.4 ounces) per fruit.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coconuts are exported without husks; de-husked nuts from Côte d'Ivoire average around 575 grams, while de-husked nuts from the Dominican Republic average nearly 700 grams.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coconuts sold domestically in coconut-producing countries are typically not de-husked.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Immature coconuts (6 to 8 months from flowering) are sold for coconut water and softer jelly-like coconut meat (known as "green coconuts", "young coconuts", or "water coconuts"), where the original coloration of the fruit is more pleasing.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Whole mature coconuts (11 to 13 months from flowering) sold for export, however, typically have the husk removed to reduce weight and volume for transport.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] This results in the naked coconut "shell" with three pores, remnants of the three carpels of the flower, more familiar in countries where coconuts are not grown locally.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] De-husked coconuts are easier for consumers to open, but have a shorter postharvest storage life of around two to three weeks at temperatures of 12 to 15 °C (54 to 59 °F) or up to 2 months at 0 to 1.5 °C (32.0 to 34.7 °F).
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] In comparison, mature coconuts with a husk can be stored for three to five months at room temperature.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The palm tree has neither a taproot nor root hairs, but a fibrous root system.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] This consists of many thin roots that grow outward from the plant near the surface.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Only a few penetrate deep into the soil for stability.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] This is known as a fibrous or adventitious root system, and is a characteristic of grass species.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] 2,000–4,000 adventitious roots may grow, each about 1 cm (1⁄2 in) in diameter.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Decayed roots are replaced regularly as the tree grows new ones.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The Swedish botanist and taxonomist Carl Linnaeus formally described the species *Cocos nucifera* in his book *Species Plantarum* in 1753.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] In 1768, in his book *The Gardeners Dictionary*, the English botanist Philip Miller redescribed the plant as *Palma cocos*, a name treated as a synonym.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] In 1891, the German botanist Otto Kuntze gave it the name *Calappa nucifera* in his *Revisio Generum Plantarum*, also treated as a synonym.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The generic name *Cocos*, and the common name, is derived from the 16th-century Portuguese word *coco*, meaning 'head' or 'skull' after the three indentations on the coconut shell that give an impression of a face.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] This apparently came from encounters in 1521 by Portuguese and Spanish explorers with Pacific Islanders, when the coconut shell reminded them of ghosts in Portuguese folklore called *coco* or *côca*.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] In the West, the fruit was originally called *nux indica*, a name used by Marco Polo in 1280 while in Sumatra.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] His term is a translation from the Arabic of the time, where it was called جوز هندي *jawz hindī*, "Indian nut".
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] *Thenga*, its Tamil/Malayalam name, was used in the detailed description of coconut found in *Itinerario* by Ludovico di Varthema published in 1510 and in the later *Hortus Indicus Malabaricus*.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The specific name *nucifera* means "nut-bearing", from the Latin words *nux* (nut) and *fera* (bearing).
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The vast majority of *Cocos*-like fossils have been recovered from only two regions in the world: New Zealand and west-central India.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] However, *Cocos*-like fossils are still putative, as they are difficult to identify.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The earliest *Cocos*-like fossil to be found was *C. zeylandica*, a fossil species with small fruits, around 3.5 cm (1+1⁄2 in) × 1.3 to 2.5 cm (1⁄2 to 1 in) in size, from the Miocene (~23 to 5.3 million years ago) of New Zealand.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Since then, numerous other fossils of similar fruits of uncertain affinity have been found in New Zealand from the Eocene, Oligocene, and possibly the Holocene.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] In the Deccan Traps of west-central India, numerous fossils of *Cocos*-like fruits, leaves, and stems have been found.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] They include morphotaxa like *Palmoxylon sundaran*, *Palmoxylon insignae*, and *Palmocarpon cocoides*.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] *Cocos*-like fossils of fruits include *Cocos intertrappeansis*, *Cocos pantii*, and *Cocos sahnii*.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Some have been tentatively identified as modern *C. nucifera*.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] These include two specimens named *C. palaeonucifera* and *C. binoriensis*, both dated by their authors to the Maastrichtian–Danian of the early Tertiary (70 to 62 million years ago).
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] *C. binoriensis* has been claimed to be the earliest known fossil of *C. nucifera*.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Only two other regions have reported *Cocos*-like fossils, namely Australia and Colombia.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] In Australia, a *Cocos*-like fossil fruit, measuring 10 cm × 9.5 cm (3+7⁄8 in × 3+3⁄4 in), was recovered from the Chinchilla Sand Formation dated to the latest Pliocene or basal Pleistocene.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Rigby (1995) assigned them to modern *Cocos nucifera* based on its size.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] In Colombia, a single *Cocos*-like fruit was recovered from the middle to late Paleocene Cerrejón Formation.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The fruit, however, was compacted in the fossilization process and it was not possible to determine if it had the diagnostic three pores that characterize members of the tribe Cocoseae.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Nevertheless, one study assigned it to *Cocos* based on the size and the ridged shape of the fruit.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Genetic studies identify the coconut's center of origin as the Central Indo-Pacific, where it has its greatest genetic diversity.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Its cultivation and spread was closely tied to migrations of the Austronesian peoples who carried coconuts to the islands they settled.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Linguistic, archaeological, and genetic evidence all points to domestication of Pacific coconuts by Austronesians in Southeast Asia during the Austronesian expansion (c.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Drift models based on wind and ocean currents show that coconuts could not have drifted across the Pacific unaided, implying that dispersal was human-assisted.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coconuts are divided into two subpopulations, a Pacific group from Island Southeast Asia and an Indo-Atlantic group from the south of the Indian subcontinent.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The Pacific group is clearly domesticated, with dwarf habit, self-pollination, and *niu vai* fruits with large endosperm-to-husk ratios.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The distribution of Pacific coconuts corresponds to regions settled by Austronesian voyagers, especially Madagascar.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The island's coconuts show genetic admixture between the two subpopulations, indicating that Pacific coconuts interbred with Indo-Atlantic coconuts there.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Although archaeological remains from 1000 to 500 BCE suggest that Indo-Atlantic coconuts were later independently cultivated by Dravidian peoples, only Pacific coconuts show clear domestication traits like dwarf habits, self-pollination, and rounded fruits.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Indo-Atlantic coconuts, in contrast, have the ancestral traits of tall habits and elongated triangular fruits.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Genetic studies have confirmed pre-Columbian populations of coconuts in Panama.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] However, it is not native and displays a genetic bottleneck resulting from a founder effect.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coconuts in the Americas are most closely related to those in the Philippines, indicating that the coconuts were not introduced naturally, such as by sea currents, but by early Austronesian sailors to the Americas from at least 4250 BCE.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] During the colonial era, Pacific coconuts were introduced to Mexico from the Spanish East Indies via the Manila galleons, starting in the 16th century.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] In contrast, Indo-Atlantic coconuts were spread by Arab and Persian traders into the East African coast.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Indo-Atlantic coconuts were introduced into the Atlantic Ocean by Portuguese ships from colonies in India and Sri Lanka, again starting in the 16th century: first to coastal West Africa, and then to the Caribbean and Brazil.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coconuts can be broadly divided into two fruit types – the ancestral *niu kafa* form with a thick-husked, angular fruit, and the *niu vai* form with a thin-husked, spherical fruit with a higher proportion of endosperm.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The *niu kafa* form is the wild ancestral type, with thick husks to protect the seed, and an angular, highly ridged shape to promote buoyancy during ocean dispersal.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] It is the dominant form in the Indo-Atlantic coconuts.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] However, they may have been selected to some extent for thicker husks for coir production, which was important in Austronesian material culture as a source for cordage in building houses and boats.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The *niu vai* form is the domesticated form dominant in Pacific coconuts.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] They were artificially selected by Austronesians for their larger endosperm-to-husk ratio and higher coconut water content, making them more useful as food and water reserves for sea voyages.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The decreased buoyancy and increased fragility of this spherical, thin-husked fruit did not matter for a species that had started to be dispersed by humans and grown in plantations.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] *Niu vai* endocarp fragments have been recovered in archaeological sites in the St.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Matthias Islands of the Bismarck Archipelago.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The fragments are dated to approximately 1000 BCE, suggesting that cultivation and artificial selection of coconuts were already practiced by the Austronesian Lapita people.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coconuts can be broadly divided into two general types based on habit: the "Tall" (var.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The two groups are genetically distinct, with the dwarf variety showing a greater degree of artificial selection for ornamental traits and for early germination and fruiting.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The tall variety is outcrossing while dwarf palms are self-pollinating, which has led to a much greater degree of genetic diversity within the tall group.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The dwarf coconut cultivars are fully domesticated, unlike the more diverse tall cultivars.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Dwarf coconuts share three genetic markers out of thirteen (rare in tall cultivars), making it likely that they originate from a single domesticated population.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Philippine and Malayan dwarf coconuts diverged early into two distinct types.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] They usually remain genetically isolated when introduced to new regions.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Numerous other dwarf cultivars developed after such introductions, hybridizing with tall cultivars.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The origin of dwarf varieties is Southeast Asia, which contain the tall cultivars genetically closest to dwarf coconuts.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Genome sequencing of tall and dwarf varieties reveals that they diverged 2 to 8 million years ago and that the dwarf variety arose through alterations in genes for the metabolism of the plant hormone gibberellin.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Another ancestral variety is the ***niu leka*** of Polynesia (the "Compact Dwarfs").
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Although it resembles dwarf coconuts (including slow growth), it is genetically distinct and was independently domesticated, likely in Tonga.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Other cultivars of *niu leka* may exist in other islands of the Pacific, and some are probably descendants of advanced crosses between Compact Dwarfs and Southeast Asian Dwarf types.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coconuts have a nearly cosmopolitan distribution due to human cultivation and dispersal.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] However, their original distribution was in the Central Indo-Pacific, in the regions of Maritime Southeast Asia and Melanesia.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The coconut palm thrives on sandy soils and is highly tolerant of salinity.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] It prefers areas with abundant sunlight and regular rainfall of between 1500 mm and 2500 mm per year.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] If rainfall is less than this, it can survive if its roots can reach the soil water table, but it cannot tolerate waterlogging.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] It grows from sea level to an altitude of 600 metres (2,000 ft) in the tropics.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] It can tolerate a dry season of one month on sandy soils inland, and as much as three months on heavier soils, but the soil must be free-draining.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] It grows on soils with a pH of 4.5 to 8 (the latter on coral atolls), but prefers a range of 5.5 to 7.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] It can resist hurricane-strength winds provided it has developed a good root system.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Wild coconuts are restricted to coastal areas in sandy, saline soils.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The fruit is adapted for ocean dispersal.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coconuts could not reach inland locations without human intervention to carry seednuts and plant seedlings.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coconut palms are normally cultivated in hot and wet tropical climates.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] They need year-round warmth and moisture to grow well and fruit.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coconut palms are hard to establish in dry climates, and cannot grow there without frequent irrigation.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] In drought conditions, the new leaves do not open well, older leaves may become desiccated, and fruit may be shed.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The extent of cultivation in the tropics is threatening a number of habitats, such as mangroves; an example of such damage to an ecoregion is in the Petenes mangroves of the Yucatán.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Uniquely among trees, coconut trees can be irrigated with sea water.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coconuts are susceptible to the phytoplasma disease, lethal yellowing.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Yellowing diseases affect plantations in Africa, India, Mexico, the Caribbean and the Pacific Region.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The coconut leaf beetle *Brontispa longissima* feeds on young leaves, and damages both seedlings and mature coconut palms.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] In 2007, the Philippines imposed a quarantine in Metro Manila and 26 provinces to stop the spread of the pest and protect the Philippine coconut industry managed by some 3.5 million farmers.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The fruit may be damaged by eriophyid coconut mites (*Aceria guerreronis*).
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] This mite infests coconut plantations, and can cause economic damage up to 60% of coconut production.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The immature seeds are infested and damaged by larvae.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Chemical control is possible, but since it needs to be repeated frequently it is impracticable on grounds of cost, environmental harm, and pesticide residues in coconut meat and coconut water.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coconut has many commercial and traditional cultivars.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] They can be sorted mainly into tall, dwarf, and hybrid cultivars (hybrids between talls and dwarfs).
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Varieties are often regional, such as Ceylon Tall, Jamaica Tall, Java Tall, and Malayan Tall.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Dwarf varieties of Pacific coconuts have been cultivated by Austronesian peoples since ancient times.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] These varieties were selected for slower growth, sweeter coconut water, and often brightly colored fruits.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Dwarf varieties include Dwarf Green and Dwarf Orange.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Varieties have been selected for diverse traits: for example, King coconut is a Sri Lankan variety with a relatively low sugar content, while Macapuno has soft jelly-like flesh that fills the whole central cavity; it is used to make sweet desserts.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Maypan is an F1 hybrid bred in Jamaica in the 1970s to resist lethal yellowing.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] However, Maypan resistance soon began to fail, possibly as early as the 1980s, and certainly by the 2000s.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Some other coconut varieties have natural resistance to lethal yellowing with alleles at microsatellites, with *Vanuatu tall* and *Sri-Lanka green dwarf* as the most resistant cultivars, while *West African tall* is especially susceptible.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coconut breeding objectives can include copra content, production of female flowers, oil content, aroma of coconut meat and water, softness and sweetness of endosperm, drought tolerance, resistance to root wilt, and resistance to eriophorid mites.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Hybrids provide higher precocity and productivity with the number of fruits than other breeds, but they produce fruits with low market acceptance for the water quality of the fruit.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Intravarietal crosses in Dwarf coconut (dwarf coconuts bred together) have been tested to provide better water quality for the coconut water market than the hybrids.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The two most common harvesting methods are by climbing and by using poles.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Climbing is the more widespread, but it is more dangerous and requires skilled workers.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Manually climbing trees is traditional in most countries and requires a posture that exerts pressure on the trunk with the feet.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Climbers employed on coconut plantations often develop musculoskeletal disorders and risk injury or death from falling.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] For safety, coconut climbers in the Philippines and Guam use a bolo knife tied with a rope to the waist to cut grooves at regular intervals on the coconut trunks.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] This makes the trunk of the tree more like a ladder, though it reduces the value of timber recovered from the trees and can admit infection.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Other methods to make climbing easier include using a system of pulleys and ropes; using pieces of vine, rope, or cloth tied to both hands or feet; using spikes attached to the feet or legs; or attaching coconut husks to the trunk with ropes.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The pole method uses a long pole with a cutting device at the end.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] In the Philippines, the traditional tool is called the *halabas* and is made from a long bamboo pole with a sickle-like blade at its tip.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Though safer and faster than climbing, it does not allow workers to examine and clean the crown of coconuts for pests and diseases.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Modern methods use hydraulic elevators mounted on tractors or ladders.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Mechanical coconut climbing devices and robots have been developed in India, Sri Lanka, and Malaysia.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The Coconut Maturity Detection Project uses imaging and machine learning to identify mature coconut bunches ready for harvesting.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] A system of bamboo bridges and ladders directly connecting the tree canopies is used in the Philippines for coconut plantations that harvest coconut sap (not fruits) for coconut vinegar and palm wine production.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] In other areas, as in Papua New Guinea, coconuts are simply collected when they fall to the ground.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Some coconut farmers in Thailand and Malaysia use southern pig-tailed macaques to harvest coconuts.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Thailand has been raising and training them to pick coconuts for around 400 years.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Training schools for pig-tailed macaques still exist in southern Thailand and in the Malaysian state of Kelantan.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals (PETA) objected to the Thailand practice in 2019.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] In 2024, world production of coconuts in shells was 65.5 million tonnes, led by Indonesia, India, and the Philippines, together having 72% of the total (table).
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] In India, four southern states account for most of India's total production: Tamil Nadu, Karnataka, Kerala, and Andhra Pradesh.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Though Kerala has the largest number of coconut trees, Tamil Nadu is the most productive per hectare.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The coconut is the official state tree of Kerala, whose name in the local language Malayalam means "coconut land".
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The main coconut-producing area in the Middle East is the Dhofar region of Oman.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The ancient coconut groves of Dhofar were mentioned by the medieval Moroccan traveller Ibn Battuta in his book *The Rihla*.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Sri Lanka established its Coconut Development Authority and Coconut Cultivation Board and Coconut Research Institute in the early British Ceylon period.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] As a rich source of lauric acid and other saturated fats, coconut oil is a dietary risk factor for cardiovascular diseases by elevating blood levels of LDL cholesterol.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Many national clinical associations recommend limiting consumption of coconut oil products, replacing them instead with foods containing unsaturated fats.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The coconut palm is grown throughout the tropics for decoration, as well as for its culinary and nonculinary uses; virtually every part of the coconut palm is used by humans in some manner and has significant economic value.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The coconut's versatility is noted in some of its names: in Sanskrit, it is *kalpa vriksha* ("the tree of the necessities of life"), while in Malay, it is *pokok seribu guna* ("the tree of a thousand uses"), and in the Philippines, it is called the "tree of life".
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] It is one of the most useful trees in the world.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Raw coconut meat is 47% water, 33% fat, 15% carbohydrates, and 3% protein (table).
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] In a reference amount of 100 grams (3.5 oz), raw coconut flesh supplies 350 calories of food energy, and is a rich source (20% or more of the Daily Value, DV) of manganese (65% DV) and copper (48% DV), with various other dietary minerals in moderate amounts (10–18% DV; table).
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Raw coconut meat has a high content of saturated fatty acids (30% of total fats), with lauric acid as the main saturated fat (15% of total; USDA source in table).
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The many culinary uses of coconuts are largely based on the edible white, fleshy part of the seed (the endosperm), known as "coconut meat".
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The meat of immature coconuts can be eaten as it is or cooked in pastries.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Mature coconut meat is tough and is processed before consumption, being made into products like coconut milk, "coconut chips" or grated and dehydrated as "desiccated coconut".
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coconut milk, used for cooking many dishes, is pressed from coconut meat.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] It can be diluted to create coconut milk beverages such as milk substitutes.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coconut milk powder, a protein-rich powder, can be processed from coconut milk.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coconut milk and coconut cream extracted from grated coconut can be added to desserts and savory dishes, or used in curries and stews.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Products made from thickened coconut milk with sugar and eggs, like coconut jam and coconut custard, are widespread in Southeast Asia.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coconut oil is used for frying and cooking.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coconut water can be drunk fresh or used in cooking.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] It can be fermented to produce a jelly-like dessert known as *nata de coco*.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coconut vinegar, made from fermented coconut water or sap, is used extensively in Southeast Asian and Goan cuisine.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coconut sap, fresh or fermented, is drunk as toddy or *tubâ* in the Philippines.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] When left to ferment on its own, it becomes palm wine.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Palm wine is distilled to produce *arrack*.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The sap can be reduced by boiling to create a sweet syrup, or reduced further to yield coconut sugar.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] A young, well-maintained tree can produce around 300 litres (79 US gallons) of toddy per year, while a 40-year-old tree may yield around 400 L (110 US gal).
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] In 2023, world production of processed coconut oil was 3.1 million tonnes, led by the Philippines with 38% of the total, and Indonesia and India as secondary producers (table).
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coconut oil is used in cooking, especially for frying.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] It can be used in liquid form like other vegetable oils, or in solid form like butter or lard.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coconut butter is a solidified coconut oil, but the name is also applied to creamed coconut, a specialty product made of coconut milk solids or puréed coconut meat and oil.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Among the many non-food uses of coconut palms, the husk and shells can be used for fuel or made into charcoal.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The husks can serve as flotation devices or as an abrasive.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The shell, freed from the husk, and heated on warm ashes, exudes an oily material that is used to soothe dental pains in traditional medicine of Cambodia.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coir fiber from husks is used in ropes, mats, brushes, and sacks, as caulking for boats, and as stuffing for mattresses.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] It is used in horticulture in potting compost, especially in orchid mix, and to make brooms in Cambodia.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coconut cups were frequently carved with scenes in relief and mounted with precious metals.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The leaves provide material for baskets and for roofing thatch; they can be woven into mats, cooking skewers, and kindling arrows.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Leaves are woven into small pouches that are filled with rice and cooked to make *pusô* and *ketupat*.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Hawaiians hollowed out coconut trunks to form drums, containers, or small canoes.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The "branches" (leaf petioles) are strong and flexible enough to make a switch.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The use of coconut branches in corporal punishment was revived in the Gilbertese community on Choiseul in the Solomon Islands in 2005.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The roots are used to make dye, a mouthwash, and a folk medicine for diarrhea and dysentery.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] A frayed piece of root can be used as a toothbrush.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] In Cambodia, the roots are used in traditional medicine.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Leftover fiber from coconut oil and coconut milk production, coconut meal, is used as livestock feed.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The dried calyx is used as fuel in wood-fired stoves.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Coconut water is traditionally used as a growth supplement in plant tissue culture and micropropagation.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] A coconut (Sanskrit: *narikela*) is used in Hindu rituals.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Often it is decorated with bright metal foils.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] It is offered during worship to a Hindu god or goddess.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Narali Poornima is celebrated on a full moon day which usually signifies the end of monsoon season in India.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The word *Narali* is derived from Marathi *naral*, "coconut".
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Fishermen give an offering of coconut to the sea to celebrate the beginning of a new fishing season, in the hope of bountiful catches.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Hindus often initiate any new activity by breaking a coconut to ensure the blessings of the gods.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The Hindu goddess of well-being and wealth, Lakshmi, is often shown holding a coconut.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] They are used in Hindu weddings as a symbol of prosperity.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The flowers are used sometimes in wedding ceremonies in Cambodia.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The Zulu Social Aid & Pleasure Club of New Orleans traditionally throws hand-decorated coconuts, one of the most valuable Mardi Gras souvenirs, to parade revelers.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The tradition began in the 1910s, and has continued since.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] In 1987, a "coconut law" was signed by Governor Edwin Edwards exempting from insurance liability any decorated coconut "handed" from a Zulu float.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The coconut is used as a target and prize in the traditional British fairground game coconut shy.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The player buys some small balls which are thrown at coconuts balanced on sticks.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The aim is to knock a coconut off the stand and win it.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] It was the main food of adherents of the now discontinued Vietnamese Coconut Religion, *Đạo Dừa*.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Some South Asian, Southeast Asian, and Pacific Ocean cultures have origin myths in which the coconut plays the main role.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] In the Hainuwele myth from Maluku, a girl emerges from the blossom of a coconut tree.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] In Maldivian folklore, one of the main myths of origin reflects the dependence of the Maldivians on the coconut tree.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] In the story of Sina and the Eel, the origin of the coconut is related as the beautiful woman Sina burying an eel, which eventually became the first coconut.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] According to urban legend, more deaths are caused by falling coconuts than by sharks annually, though the truth is actually the reverse.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Literary evidence from the *Ramayana* and Sri Lankan chronicles indicates that the coconut was present in the Indian subcontinent before the 1st century BCE.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] The earliest direct description is given by Cosmas Indicopleustes in his *Topographia Christiana* written around 545, where the coconut is called "the great nut of India".
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] Another early mention is the "One Thousand and One Nights" story of Sinbad the Sailor, who bought and sold a coconut during his fifth voyage.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] In March 1521, Antonio Pigafetta described the coconut in his journal in Italian with the word "*cocho*", plural "*cochi*".
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] This followed the first European crossing of the Pacific Ocean during the Magellan circumnavigation.
[src:coconut-shy/coconut] He explained how at Guam "they eat coconuts" ("*mangiano cochi*") and that the natives there "anoint the body and the hair with coconut and beniseed oil" ("*ongieno el corpo et li capili co oleo de cocho et de giongioli*").
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] The ***Daily Pilot*** is a daily newspaper published by the *Los Angeles Times* to serve the communities of Sunset Beach, Huntington Beach, Fountain Valley, Newport Beach, Costa Mesa and Laguna Beach in Orange County, California.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] The *Daily Pilot* is one of the publications of Times Community News, which is a subsidiary of the *Los Angeles Times*.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] Swain, of Long Beach, founded a weekly newspaper called the *Newport News.* In July 1907, Swain sold the *News* to Raymond Wayman, former editor of the *Huntington Beach News*.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] The sale was for $10 and Swain left town without telling Wayman that the business was up to $2,000 in debt.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] In June 1908, Wayman sold the paper to Walter A.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] Cornelius, who published it for a dozen years until 1920, when he sold the *News* to Charles B.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] Meyer, owner of the *Chandler Arizonan*, purchased the *News* from Wheatley.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] In 1925, Meyer purchased the *Balboa Bulletin* and *Costa Mesa Courier* from J.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] Winterbourne and consolidated them together to form the *Balboa Times*.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] In 1928, Meyer was sued for libel by H.L.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] Sherman, publisher of a rival paper called the *Harbor Herald* at Newport Beach.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] The jury deliberated for under an hour and then awarded Sherman $1, plus another $100 for attorney's fee.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] In 1946, Meyers retired as publisher after two decades and was succeeded by Sam D.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] Porter, who had acquired a controlling interest in the business.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] In March 1948, Porter expanded the paper from a semi-weekly into a daily with a circulation of 2,500.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] The combined *Newport News* and *Balboa Times* was called the *Daily News-Times.* In December 1948, Porter dissolved his partnership with Lucius Smith III, who became a co-owner at some point, and the business entered receivership.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] Rex published the paper for a month, before it was sold at auction to Victor W.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] Cotton, former publishers of the *South Gate Press-Tribune* and *Indo Date Palm*.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] Shortly after the sale, the new owners acquired the *Newport Bay Post* and *Shopping News*.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] In March 1949, the *News-Times* reverted to a semi-weekly.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] In April 1949, Ben Otis Reddick, publisher of the *Newport-Balboa Press*, acquired the company from Weathers and Cotton.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] In 1954, Reddick consolidated the *News-Times* and the *Press* to form the *Newport Harbor News-Press*.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] In 1961, Times Mirror purchased the *Orange Coast Daily Pilot*.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] At that time the paper had three editions: *The Costa Mesa Globe Herald Daily Pilot*, the *Newport Harbor Daily Pilot*, and *Huntington Beach Daily Pilot*.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] The combined paid circulation was 17,000.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] In April 1962, Reddick sold the *News-Press* to the Ridder family, who owned a chain papers including the *Long Beach Press-Telegram* and *Pasadena Star-News*.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] In September 1962, Times Mirror acquired the *News-Press*, and then merged it into the *Daily Pilot*.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] The *Daily Pilot* and three weekly papers were acquired by Ingersoll Publications in 1982, which purchased the *Huntington Beach Independent* in 1985.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] The *Daily Pilot* and *Independent* were sold to Adams Communications in 1988.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] Page, former publisher of the *Chicago Sun-Times*, bought the papers with financial backing from New York businessman Elliot Stein.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] The *Glendale News Press* and *Burbank Leader* were acquired a week later.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] In 1993, Times Mirror bought the *Daily Pilot*, *News Press*, *Independent* and *Leader* from Page Group Publishing.
[src:coconut-shy/daily-pilot] In 2016, the *Huntington Beach Independent* and the *Laguna Beach Coastline Pilot* were merged into the *Daily Pilot*.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Nesbit was born in 1858 at 38 Lower Kennington Lane, Kennington, Surrey (now London), the daughter of an agricultural chemist, John Collis Nesbit, who died in March 1862, before her fourth birthday.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Her mother was Sarah Green (née Alderton).
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] The ill health of Edith's sister Mary meant that the family travelled for some years, living variously in Brighton, Buckinghamshire, France (Dieppe, Rouen, Paris, Tours, Poitiers, Angoulême, Bordeaux, Arcachon, Pau, Bagnères-de-Bigorre, and Dinan in Brittany), Spain and Germany.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Mary was engaged in 1871 to the poet Philip Bourke Marston, but later that year she died of tuberculosis in Normandy.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] After Mary's death, Edith and her mother settled for three years at Halstead Hall, Halstead, north-west Kent, a location that inspired *The Railway Children*, although the distinction has also been claimed by the Derbyshire town of New Mills.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] When Nesbit was 17, the family moved back to Lewisham in south-east London.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] There is a Lewisham Council plaque to her at 28 Elswick Road.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] In 1877, at the age of 18, Nesbit met the bank clerk Hubert Bland, her elder by three years.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Seven months pregnant, she married Bland on 22 April 1880, but did not initially live with him, as Bland remained with his mother.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Early on, Nesbit found that another woman, Maggie Doran, who lived with his mother, believed she was Hubert's fiancée and had likewise borne him a child.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Nesbit's children by Bland were Paul Cyril Bland (1880–1940), to whom *The Railway Children* was dedicated, Mary Iris Bland (1881–1965), who married John Austin D Phillips in 1907, and Fabian Bland (1885–1900).
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] A more serious blow came in 1886, when she discovered that her friend Alice Hoatson was pregnant by him.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] She had previously agreed to adopt Hoatson's child and allow Hoatson to live with her as their housekeeper.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] After she discovered the truth, she and her husband quarrelled violently and she suggested that Hoatson and the baby, Rosamund, should leave; her husband threatened to leave Edith if she disowned the baby and its mother.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Hoatson remained with them as a housekeeper and secretary and became pregnant by Bland again 13 years later.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Edith again adopted Hoatson's child, John.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Nesbit's son Fabian died aged 15 after a tonsil operation.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Nesbit felt guilt over this, having fed him shortly before the general anaesthetic and then leaving him unattended afterwards, not realising that he might choke to death on regurgitated food.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] She subsequently dedicated several books to him, including *The Story of the Treasure Seekers* and its sequels.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Nesbit's adopted daughter Rosamund collaborated with her on *Cat Tales*.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Nesbit admired the artist and Marxian socialist William Morris.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] The couple joined the founders of the Fabian Society in 1884, after which their son Fabian was named, and jointly edited its journal *Today*.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Nesbit and Bland dallied with the Social Democratic Federation, but found it too radical.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Nesbit was a prolific lecturer and writer on socialism in the 1880s.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] She and her husband co-wrote under the pseudonym "Fabian Bland", However, the joint work dwindled as her success rose as a children's author.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] She was a guest speaker at the London School of Economics, which had been founded by other Fabian Society members.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Edith lived from 1899 to 1920 at Well Hall, Eltham, in south-east London, which makes fictional appearances in several of her books, such as *The Red House*.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] From 1911 she kept a second home on the Sussex Downs at Crowlink, Friston, East Sussex.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] She and her husband entertained many friends, colleagues and admirers at Well Hall.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] On 20 February 1917, some three years after Bland died, Nesbit married Thomas "the Skipper" Tucker in Woolwich, where he was captain of the Woolwich Ferry.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Although she was the family breadwinner and has the father in *The Railway Children* declare that "[g]irls are just as clever as boys, and don’t you forget it!", Nesbit did not champion women's rights.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Towards the end of her life, Nesbit moved first to Crowlink, then with the Skipper to two conjoined properties which were Royal Flying Corps buildings, 'Jolly Boat' and 'Long Boat', at Jesson, St Mary's Bay, New Romney, Kent.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Nesbit lived in 'Jolly Boat' and the Skipper in 'Long Boat'.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Nesbit died in 'The Long Boat', in 1924, probably from lung cancer (she "smoked incessantly"), and was buried in the churchyard of St Mary in the Marsh.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Her husband Thomas died at the same address on 17 May 1935.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Edith's son Paul Bland was an executor of Thomas Tucker's will.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Nesbit's first published works were poems.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] She was under 20 in March 1878, when the monthly magazine *Good Words* printed her poem "Under the Trees".
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] In all she published about 40 books for children, including novels, storybooks and picture books.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Works of William Shakespeare adapted by her for children have been translated.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] She also published almost as many books jointly with others.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] In 2011, a book was published by the granddaughter of Ada J.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Graves that suggested that Nesbit had 'plagiarised' parts of the plot of *The Railway Children* from *The House by the Railway* by Graves.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] It was asserted that the Graves book had appeared in 1896, nine years prior to *The Railway Children*, and various similarities between the two books were identified.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Subsequent studies disagreed with that conclusion: Online magazine *Tor.com* discovered that although the Graves book was part of a series started in 1896, that particular book wasn't published until 1906, so both books had actually been released in 1906.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Some other similarities were also suggested to be mere coincidences, although it was acknowledged that Nesbit sometimes repeated plot elements in her own books and also used ideas from others, such as H.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Briggs also credits Nesbit with inventing the children's adventure story.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Among Nesbit's best-known books are *The Story of the Treasure Seekers* (1899) and *The Wouldbegoods* (1901), which tell of the Bastables, a middle-class family fallen on relatively hard times.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] *The Railway Children* is also popularised by a 1970 film version.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Gore Vidal called the time-travel book, *The Story of the Amulet*, one where "Nesbit's powers of invention are at their best." Her children's writing also included plays and collections of verse.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Nesbit has been cited as the creator of modern children's fantasy.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Her innovations placed realistic contemporary children in real-world settings with magical objects (which would now be classed as contemporary fantasy) and adventures and sometimes travel to fantastic worlds.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] This influenced directly or indirectly many later writers, including P.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Travers (of *Mary Poppins*), Edward Eager, Diana Wynne Jones and J.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Lewis too paid heed to her in the *Narnia* series and mentions the Bastable children in *The Magician's Nephew*, which, in its scenes of Jadis (a.k.a. the White Witch) in 19th century London, borrows from a similar sequences in Nesbit's *The Story of the Amulet*.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Science fiction and fantasy writer Michael Moorcock adopted Nesbit's character of Oswald Bastable for a trilogy of steampunk novels beginning with *The Warlord of the Air*.
[src:coconut-shy/e-nesbit] Aside from an episode of the BBC's 'A Ghost Story for Christmas' from her autobiographical *Long Ago When I was Young* (published 1966), Nesbit has been the subject of five biographies.
